Delta Sharing
=============
Data provider -> Delta sharing protocol -> Data Recipient
The data provide can share delta lake tables via a delta sharing server, which implements the server side component of the protocol.
Works - the data recipient who wants to query a source table such as the orders table start by sending a request to the data sharing server. the server checks the access permissions and see whether this access is allowed, If so it checks the underlying table files in the cloud storage system like Amazon S3 it generates temporaray URL's for accessing those specifix files. Then it send these URL's back to the client. The client now can open these https links to actually transfer the relevent objects directly from the cloud object store. This mean that with this protocol, you can share massive datasets as it directly leverages the cloud optimized infrastructure for data transfer.
In databricks you have a integrated secure delta sharing server and you can set access permissions using Unity Catalog.
you can just create share and grant permissions
CREATE SHARE Bookstore;
ALTER SHARE bookstore
ADD TABLE orders;

GRANT SELECT ON SHARE bookstore TO publisher1

Two ways of sharing
1. Databricks-to-Databricks sharing protocol - share data between databricks clients, collection of tables, views, volumnes, and notebooks.
2. Databricks open sharing protocol - share data with users on any computing platform.

Costs
======
Delta sharing does not require data replication.
Egress cost - Within a region: no egress cost, Cross-clouds or cross regions: cloud vendor charges data egress fees, instead: (if no egress can use cloudfare etc..)

Limitations
===========
1. read-only access model
2. data format constraints - only delta tables are supported for sharing.

